=== Disability and Functional Capacity
<subsec:disability>

*Housebound and Bedbound Prevalence.*
Approximately 25% of ME/CFS patients are housebound or bedbound @Jason2017housebound. On worst days, 61% report being bedbound and 75% are housebound or bedbound. The housebound population demonstrates dramatically worse functional status: Physical Functioning scores of 17.1 versus 42.0 in non-housebound patients, Social Functioning of 10.2 versus 30.7, and 86% receiving disability benefits compared to 57% of non-housebound patients @Jason2017housebound.

*Severity Classification.*
Functional capacity varies by severity:

    / *Mild ($tilde$25% of patients)*: Able to work part-time or full-time with substantially reduced other activities; approximately 50% reduction from pre-illness function
    / *Moderate ($tilde$50% of patients)*: Substantially reduced activity; unable to work; requires rest periods; approximately 30–50% of pre-illness function
    / *Severe ($tilde$20% of patients)*: Largely housebound; limited to minimal activities of daily living; approximately 5–15% of pre-illness function
    / *Very Severe ($tilde$5% of patients)*: Bedbound; unable to perform most activities of daily living; often unable to tolerate sensory stimulation; less than 5% of pre-illness function

*Work Disability.*
Employment rates range from 20–41% across studies, with 35–69% unemployed due to illness @CastroMarrero2019employment. In a large Spanish cohort (n=1,086), 58.6% were unemployed, with 66% on sick leave and 34% receiving disability benefits. Risk factors for work disability include age over 50 years (OR 2.21), higher fatigue scores (OR 2.09), severe depression (OR 1.98), and autonomic dysfunction (OR 2.21) @CastroMarrero2019employment. Only 13% of ME/CFS patients maintain full-time employment.
